🟦 MySQL — Simple Hierarchy
MySQL Server
   └── Database
          └── Tables
                 └── Rows
Example:
bankappdb
   ├── users
   ├── transactions
Here:
👉 Database = Logical container
👉 Tables live directly inside database
So when you wrote:
jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/bankappdb
You are connecting to:
DATABASE → bankappdb
________________________________________
🟩 PostgreSQL — Extra Layer (Schema)
Postgres adds one more level.
PostgreSQL Server
   └── Database
          └── Schema
                └── Tables
Example:
bankdb
   ├── public.users
   ├── auth.users
   ├── payments.transactions
Here:
👉 Schema = Folder inside database
👉 Used for:
•	multi-team separation
•	security boundaries
•	microservices ownership
💡 Default schema is:
public
So most beginners don’t notice schemas initially.
________________________________________
🟪 MongoDB — Totally Different Thinking
MongoDB is NoSQL.
MongoDB Server
   └── Database
         └── Collection
               └── Documents (JSON)
Example:
bankappdb
   ├── users (collection)
   ├── transactions (collection)
Instead of tables:
collections
Instead of rows:
documents
Example document:
{
  "name": "Aditya",
  "balance": 5000
}
No fixed columns required.







